    <!-- Article Content -->
    <article class="mt-20 prose dark:prose-invert max-w-4xl border-t border-hairline pt-16">
      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink font-sans mb-6">Evaluating Keyword Density: Avoiding Search Engine Over-Optimization and Keyword Stuffing</h2>
      <div class="text-body text-sm md:text-base font-sans leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>
          Search engine optimization (SEO) depends on helping search crawler bots identify the primary topics of a webpage. Incorporating relevant keywords and variations is essential. However, repeating keywords excessively—known as **keyword stuffing**—triggers search filter warnings.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">What is Keyword Density?</h3>
        <p>
          Keyword density is a percentage index that measures how frequently a specific term occurs relative to the total word count of the document.
          <br />
          <strong class="block my-2 text-center text-ink font-mono text-xs">Keyword Density = (Term Count / Total Words) &times; 100%</strong>
          For example, if your article contains 100 words, and your target phrase occurs 3 times, your density is 3%.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Recommended SEO Densities</h3>
        <p>
          In modern search indexing algorithms, there is no single "perfect" keyword density. However, general SEO copy guidelines suggest:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-3 font-sans text-sm">
          <li><strong>1.0% to 2.5%:</strong> The target sweet spot. Keywords are present enough to signal topic relevance without looking unnatural.</li>
          <li><strong>Over 3.0%:</strong> Over-optimization warning zone. Exceeding 3% can trigger spam filter flags, hurting organic search rankings.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Understanding 1-Word, 2-Word, and 3-Word Combinations</h3>
        <p>
          Analyzing text length using multi-word phrases offers more depth:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 font-sans text-sm">
          <li><strong>1-Word Keywords:</strong> Focuses on individual key nouns (e.g. `mortgage` or `loan`). We automatically filter out common stop words like `the` or `and` to highlight meaningful keywords.</li>
          <li><strong>2-Word Phrases (Bigrams):</strong> Traces core concepts like `interest rate` or `tax calculator`.</li>
          <li><strong>3-Word Phrases (Trigrams):</strong> Captures specific long-tail search queries like `compound interest calculator`. Checking these phrases helps ensure key search intent triggers are mapped.</li>
        </ul>
      
<h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">The Truth About Keyword Density in Modern SEO</h3>
        <p>
          A common mistake made by content writers is over-optimizing text by repeating target keywords too many times. Historically, search engines relied on simple keyword counts to index pages, which led to keyword stuffing. Today, search algorithms are far more sophisticated, using semantic search, machine learning, and TF-IDF (Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency) to analyze the overall context and depth of your content.
        </p>
        <p>
          To maintain an optimal keyword density, aim for a ratio between 1% and 2% for your primary keyword. Exceeding a 2.5% density can flag your page as spam, causing search engines to lower your organic search rankings.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Walkthrough: Analyzing Content for Over-Optimization</h3>
        <p>
          Let's walk through how to audit a draft blog post for keyword density. Suppose you have written an article about a "budget calculator" and want to check if you have used the term too frequently.
        </p>
        <p>
          First, copy the text of your article and paste it into the analyzer. Review the dashboard to see the frequency of single words and multi-word phrases. If the phrase "budget calculator" has a density of 3.8%, your content is over-optimized. Edit the text by replacing some instances with synonyms (such as "financial planner" or "budget tool") to distribute keywords naturally, keeping your density in the healthy 1-2% range.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">LSI Keywords and Topical Authority</h3>
        <p>
          Instead of focusing solely on your primary keyword, search engines look for Latent Semantic Indexing (LSI) keywords—which are related terms and concepts that naturally appear in discussions around a topic. For example, an article about a "mortgage calculator" should naturally contain terms like "interest rate," "amortization schedule," "down payment," and "monthly payment." Including these related terms helps demonstrate topical authority to search engines, which improves rankings without relying on repetitive primary keywords.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Avoiding Over-Optimization Penalties</h3>
        <p>
          Search engine penalties for keyword stuffing are automated and can severely drop your website's organic traffic. To keep your writing safe, write for human readers first, using clear formatting and subheadings. After drafting, use this client-side keyword density tool to verify that your keyword ratios are balanced. Since our tool processes all text locally in your browser memory, your draft content remains completely private and secure.
        </p>        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Understanding Co-occurrence and Latent Semantic Indexing (LSI)</h3>
        <p>
          Modern search engine algorithms have evolved past simple keyword density matching. Search engines now utilize Latent Semantic Indexing (LSI) and co-occurrence models to analyze search relevance. They look for related secondary keywords that naturally accompany your main topic. For example, if you write about "mortgage calculator", search engines expect to find terms like "interest rate", "loan term", and "amortization". Evaluating keyword frequency and checking for semantic co-occurrence ensures your content covers all necessary subtopics, increasing search engine trust.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <!-- FAQ Section -->
    
